## Market Context (April 2026)

A Brussels think tank (reported Euronews, 17 Apr 2026) found that 16 EU
countries have defence agencies directly exposed to US cloud providers.
7 more use European contractors that themselves depend on US infrastructure.
Microsoft already exercised a real kill switch in 2025 — blocking ICC
prosecutor accounts after US sanctions. This is no longer a theoretical risk.

Key legal mechanism: the US CLOUD Act allows the US government to compel
data access from any US-incorporated cloud provider regardless of where
data is physically stored. "Sovereign cloud" offerings from AWS, Azure, and
GCP (EU regions, sovereign zones) do NOT protect against this — experts call
it "sovereign-washing." Software updates can be blocked under sanctions even
if data stays in Europe.

This validates Noblinks Lens's target cloud list (EU-owned providers only)
and makes the compliance engine a primary product differentiator, not a
secondary feature. Target customers include not just cost-conscious startups
but defence agencies, public sector bodies, critical infrastructure operators,
and any company subject to NIS2 or handling sensitive EU citizen data.

