### 9.10 — Migration Playbook ("We're going — what's the plan?")

The CEO has two responses to the report:

  Path A: "Score is 75%. Let's wait."
          → Lens retains the customer. Watch Mode runs. Alert fires at 90%.

  Path B: "I don't care. Start planning the migration."
          → Lens must serve this too. Otherwise the product becomes
            irrelevant the moment the decision is made.

Path B is where Lens extends its value into the migration itself.
When the CEO says "we're going," the report surfaces a structured,
phased Migration Playbook — not a generic guide, but one built from
the actual services detected in their account.

**What the Migration Playbook contains:**

```
Migration Playbook — AWS → OVHcloud
Generated for: [account name]
Target: OVHcloud (74% compatible · estimated saving €8,400/mo)

─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

PHASE 1 — Quick wins (Week 1–2)
Compatible services, low effort. Move these first.

  EC2 (12 instances) → OVHcloud Public Cloud Instances
    Map t3.medium → B2-7 (2 vCPU, 7GB). Terraform provider available.

  S3 (4 buckets) → OVHcloud Object Storage
    S3-compatible API. Change endpoint + access keys. No code changes.

  RDS Postgres (2 instances) → OVHcloud Managed Databases
    Full Postgres parity. pg_dump / pg_restore migration path.

─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

PHASE 2 — Moderate migration (Month 1–2)
Partial matches. Compatible with known effort.

  EKS (1 cluster) → Self-managed Kubernetes on OVHcloud
    Use Cluster API or kubeadm. Control plane self-managed.
    Hetzner CCM + CSI drivers available for OVHcloud equivalent.

  ELB (3 load balancers) → OVHcloud Load Balancer
    HTTP/HTTPS supported. TCP passthrough available.
    Health check configuration differs — review before cutover.

─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

PHASE 3 — Re-architecture required (Month 2–4)
No direct match. Options available but require code changes.

  Lambda (8 functions) → Containerise + deploy on OVHcloud VMs
    Option A: Docker + systemd (simplest, no orchestration)
    Option B: Knative on Kubernetes cluster from Phase 2
    Estimated effort: 2–4 weeks per function depending on complexity.

  Cognito (1 user pool) → Self-hosted Keycloak on OVHcloud
    Full OAuth2/OIDC compatibility. SDK config change only after setup.
    Estimated effort: 3–5 days including data migration.

─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

PHASE 4 — Strategic decisions (No EU equivalent)
No announced roadmap. Decide: replace, self-host, or accept dependency.

  SageMaker (1 endpoint) → Options:
    A: Keep on AWS temporarily (hybrid period — CLOUD Act risk persists)
    B: Self-host MLflow + model serving on OVHcloud GPU instances
    C: Replace with open-source inference server (TorchServe / Triton)

  Rekognition (1 collection) → Options:
    A: Self-host open-source CV model (InsightFace, DeepFace)
    B: Remove feature from EU-facing product until EU equivalent exists

─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

HYBRID PERIOD WARNING:
During migration, you will operate across both AWS and OVHcloud.
CLOUD Act exposure persists until all data is off US infrastructure.
Estimated hybrid period: 6–10 weeks at this complexity level.

─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

ESTIMATED TIMELINE: 10–14 weeks
ESTIMATED COST DURING TRANSITION: +€3,200/mo (running both clouds)
POST-MIGRATION SAVING: €8,400/mo
BREAK-EVEN: Month 1 after full migration
```

**Why this extends Lens's lifetime:**

The customer uses Lens throughout the migration — not just before the
decision. Each phase completion triggers a re-scan to verify the move
and update the readiness score. The playbook becomes the migration
project plan. Lens is open every week.

